You can query through the related model in `filter` to get your desired result - Runs, with run results of passed/no run like so.

`Run.objects.filter(run_results__result__in=[&#39;P&#39;, &#39;N&#39;])`

    class RunQuerySet(QuerySet):
        
        def passed_or_no_run(self): 
            return self.filter(run_results__result__in=[&#39;P&#39;, &#39;N&#39;])

You would need to use the &lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/topics/db/managers/#creating-a-manager-with-queryset-methods&quot;&gt;`as_manager`&lt;/a&gt; method to link a custom `QuerySet` to your model:

    class RunQuerySet(QuerySet):
    
        def passed_or_no_run(self): 
            return self.filter(run_results__result__in=[&#39;P&#39;, &#39;N&#39;])

    class Run(TimeStampedModel):
       RUN_TYPE_CHOICES = (
           (MANUAL_RUN, &#39;Manual&#39;),
           (AUTOMATED_RUN, &#39;Automated&#39;),
        )
        run_type = models.CharField(max_length=1, choices=RUN_TYPE_CHOICES)

        objects = RunQuerySet.as_manager()

Given an `QuerySet` instance of the `Run` model, you can execute `passed_or_no_run` like this:

    runs = Run.objects.all()
    runs.passed_or_no_run()

Now, instead of *all* run instances, you only get the instances where the `run_type` value is either `P` or `N`

